A x B represents the Cartesian product of sets A and B, which consists of all possible ordered pairs (a, b) where a is an element of A and b is an element of B. Similarly, B x A represents the Cartesian product of sets B and A.

A x B = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 2), (2, 3), (2, 4), (3, 2), (3, 3), (3, 4)}
B x A = {(2, 1), (2, 2), (2, 3), (3, 1), (3, 2), (3, 3), (4, 1), (4, 2), (4, 3)}

Now, we will find the intersection of A x B and B x A, which consists of the ordered pairs that are present in both sets.

A x B ∩ B x A = {}

There are no common ordered pairs in A x B and B x A, so the intersection is an empty set.
